</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 13 Oct 2018 18:11:53 +0100</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2018-10-13:/2018/10/13/neurofedora-update-week-41.html</guid><category>Community</category><category>Computational neuroscience</category><category>Free software</category><category>NEST</category><category>Fedora</category><category>NeuroFedora</category></item><item><title>NeuroFedora: towards a ready to use Free/Open source environment for neuroscientists</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2018/10/06/neurofedora-towards-a-ready-to-use-free-open-source-environment-for-neuroscientists.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;I have recently resurrected the &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://fedoraproject.org/wiki/SIGs/NeuroFedora"&gt;NeuroFedora SIG&lt;/a&gt;. We aim to make
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://getfedora.org"&gt;Fedora&lt;/a&gt; a ready to use platform for neuroscientists, so that they can
focus on the science. Read on to learn more!&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 06 Oct 2018 00:19:32 +0100</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2018-10-06:/2018/10/06/neurofedora-towards-a-ready-to-use-free-open-source-environment-for-neuroscientists.html</guid><category>Community</category><category>Computational neuroscience</category><category>Fedora</category><category>Free software</category><category>Linux</category><category>NEST</category><category>Neuron</category><category>Numpy</category><category>Pandas</category><category>Planet</category><category>Python</category><category>Reproducible research</category><category>Sumatra</category><category>TeX</category></item><item><title>Testing out Sumatra: a tool for managing iterations of simulations/analyses</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2018/05/12/testing-out-sumatra-a-tool-for-managing-iterations-of-simulations-analyses.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;When working on projects that require multiple iterations of
simulations and/or analyses, it's really quite hard to keep track of
the changes one makes and how the results vary. &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://neuralensemble.org/sumatra/"&gt;Sumatra&lt;/a&gt; is a tool
that is developed to help researchers manage such projects.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 12 May 2018 20:53:25 +0100</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2018-05-12:/2018/05/12/testing-out-sumatra-a-tool-for-managing-iterations-of-simulations-analyses.html</guid><category>Python</category><category>Reproducible research</category><category>Computational neuroscience</category><category>Sumatra</category><category>Fedora</category><category>Planet</category></item><item><title>Bringing together Gitter, IRC, and Slack channels in one place on Riot</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2017/07/12/bringing-together-gitter-irc-and-slack-channels-in-one-place-on-riot.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;Different teams use different platforms to communicate within themselves. When teams on different communication platforms want to collaborate, though - there's a bit of an issue. In this post, I document how one can setup channels on various platforms (&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://slack.com"&gt;Slack&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_Relay_Chat"&gt;IRC&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://gitter.im"&gt;Gitter&lt;/a&gt;) and bring them all together on &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://riot.im"&gt;Riot&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 12 Jul 2017 13:55:17 +0100</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2017-07-12:/2017/07/12/bringing-together-gitter-irc-and-slack-channels-in-one-place-on-riot.html</guid><category>Community</category><category>Computational neuroscience</category><category>Fedora</category><category>FlatPak</category><category>Free software</category><category>Gitter</category><category>Linux</category><category>Planet</category></item><item><title>A channel for neuroscientists on Gitter</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2017/06/26/a-channel-for-neuroscientists-on-gitter.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;I've come across a few mailing lists for neuroscientists, but I couldn't find a chat channel. While mailing lists suit certain purposes, open source communities tend to use a combination of mailing lists and chat channels - each platform serves different purposes. TLDR: here's a new chat channel on &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/gitterHQ"&gt;Gitter&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://gitter.im/neuroscience-central/Lobby"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt; for everything neuroscience related. It is also accessible using the &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://webchat.freenode.net/?channels=#neuroscience-central-lobby"&gt;IRC&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://riot.im/app/#/room/#neuroscience-central-lobby:matrix.org"&gt;Riot&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Mon, 26 Jun 2017 10:30:01 +0100</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2017-06-26:/2017/06/26/a-channel-for-neuroscientists-on-gitter.html</guid><category>Community</category><category>Computational neuroscience</category><category>Gitter</category><category>Planet</category></item><item><title>Python - analysing large files - some notes to self</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2017/01/10/python-analysing-large-files-some-notes-to-self.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;I use Python to post process large amounts of spike data from my simulations. This post documents some observations I've made while writing my scripts.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 10 Jan 2017 15:38:26 +0000</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2017-01-10:/2017/01/10/python-analysing-large-files-some-notes-to-self.html</guid><category>Computational neuroscience</category><category>Fedora</category><category>Programming</category><category>Gnuplot</category><category>Matplotlib</category><category>Python</category><category>Pandas</category><category>Numpy</category></item><item><title>Two new planets for neuroscientists</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2016/11/26/two-new-planets-for-neuroscientists.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;No, not heavenly bodies, feed aggregators.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 26 Nov 2016 14:53:57 +0000</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2016-11-26:/2016/11/26/two-new-planets-for-neuroscientists.html</guid><category>Fedora</category><category>Community</category><category>Computational neuroscience</category><category>Git</category></item><item><title>On jargon</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2016/10/17/on-jargon.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;When we speak of jargon, it is usually because we heard something we couldn't make sense of. We focus on how it adversely affects the listener. The truth is, it also affects the speaker if the speaker does indeed intend to get the point across. In this post I discuss how it affects my work and me and I try to document what I can do to improve my communications to make it easier for my listeners and me to understand each other correctly.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Mon, 17 Oct 2016 08:26:30 +0100</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2016-10-17:/2016/10/17/on-jargon.html</guid><category>Computational neuroscience</category><category>Fedora</category><category>Social</category></item><item><title>Using NEURON - Part II</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2016/09/02/using-neuron-part-ii.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;This second post on using &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.neuron.yale.edu/neuron/"&gt;NEURON&lt;/a&gt; documents how to run an existing model, for example, from &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://senselab.med.yale.edu/ModelDB/ModelList.cshtml?id=1882"&gt;ModelDB&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 02 Sep 2016 13:39:16 +0100</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2016-09-02:/2016/09/02/using-neuron-part-ii.html</guid><category>Fedora</category><category>Neuron</category><category>Computational neuroscience</category></item></channel></rss>